<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
April 26, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Senator Cochrans Exemplary Actions"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>
<P>
On occasion, there is honor among politicians and it is worth our taking notice. Senator Thad Cochran of Mississippi is Chairman of the Senate GOP Conference. It is one of the top leadership positions in the Senate. He is sort of the Chairman of the Board of all Republican Senators. He has a significant staff. He has occupied the position for six years and no one has even hinted about running against him for that leadership position in the next Congress. Cochran is a shoo-in for a fourth term in the Senate this November.<P> 
But Thad Cochran helped freshmen Senators engineer term limits for the Senate Leadership and Committee Chairmen. As part of a reform package, it was adopted by the majority at the beginning of the 104th Congress last year. Cochran was one of the very few senior Senators to have assisted the freshmen in getting the reforms they sought.<P>
The term limits for Leadership provision grandfathered Cochran and others so the six year time clock would not apply to them for another couple of Congresses. But Thad Cochran is an honorable man. Having been a chief proponent of six year term limits for the Leadership, and his six years as Leader being up at the end of this Congress, Cochran announced that he will not seek re-election as Chairman of the Conference.<P> 
Thus Cochran sets the sort of example inside the Senate which Senator Malcolm Wallop set in 1994 in Wyoming. Wallop was an ardent opponent of term limits. However, the people of Wyoming voted for term limits by more than 70% of the vote. Their vote also grandfathered Wallop, who didn't agree with the outcome, but he felt the people had spoken so he announced that he would abide by their will and retire. That forced the hand of his colleague Alan Simpson who also announced his retirement from the Senate, after three terms, at the end of this Congress. <P>
Cochran's announcement was a thunderbolt in the Senate. Here is a Senator who is actually putting into practice what he says he believes. Cochran's actions will likely effect what other Senators, who have been in the Leadership for many years, will do as well. <P>
One can only speculate what it will mean for Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole. If Dole loses the Presidency, the question of his continued leadership in the Senate will be front and center. Dole was first elected Leader following the 1984 election. He has been either Majority Leader or Minority Leader ever since. 
<P>Cochran's principled actions will put Dole in a box. Even though the reforms passed by Senate Republicans specifically exempt the Majority Leader, will Bob Dole, should he lose the Presidency, dare to come back to his colleagues and say, "Others are leaving after six years, but I want my job back for the 13th and 14th year?" I frankly doubt, now that Cochran has done what he has done, Dole would get by with it. For Dateline Washington, I'm Paul Weyrich. 

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
<center>
