<html>
<head>
<title>Smut assault forces return to censorship</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><p><br>   
<i>January 17, 1997</i><br>     
<h2>Smut assault forces return to censorship</h2>     
<br>By <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a>     
<p>
<dd>I remember the first time I saw a dirty picture as a child. I was babysitting a neighbor's kids in the apartment building where I lived and spied a pin-up calendar hung inside an open closet door. I recall being scared to close the door, lest anyone remember it had been left ajar, and too timid to take a closer look, in case either parent returned unexpectedly. Little impression of the picture itself remains: a buxom blonde in Li'l Abner costume, breasts partially exposed.
<dd>Such innocent times. I thought of that picture again recently on a trip to Manhattan. I was tired after a long day of meetings and speeches and decided to spend the evening in my room at the Yale Club, ordering in room service and mindlessly watching TV. Unlike most hotels these days, the Yale Club offers no in-room movies, just basic cable service. 
<dd>Too lazy to cross the room and examine the TV Guide, I used the remote to move from channel to channel looking for something to watch. Shortly after 10:00 PM, my channel surfing swept me into unchartered waters. Suddenly I was staring at writhing, naked bodies: three young men, black and white, one wearing only a studded dog-collar; another, a gold cross hanging between his pectorals. 
<dd>I saw more. Simulated sex acts, close ups of tumescent genitals and other body parts and most memorably, the faces of the men, boys really, barely older than my children. After a few minutes, I switched the channel, unable to watch anymore, not even to try to learn what program it was I had happened upon. 
<dd>As shocking as the experience was, I'll survive this unwanted brush with gay pornography. But what about children or adolescents who happen to tune in? And they will, especially those who are already most vulnerable, whose parents aren't around or don't care what their kids are up to at 10 o'clock at night. What effect will those pictures have on the young? 
<dd>After this episode I learned that the cable franchise in New York City has tried unsuccessfully to limit this channel to those customers who send in postcards requesting it, free of charge. A federal district court judge considered this imposition too onerous, stigmatizing those with pornographic tastes. Apparently the judge did not feel it too burdensome to require parents to learn to program their cable boxes if they wished to keep images of sodomy off the family TV. He issued an injunction prohibiting the franchise from blocking the channel, which now remains part of the basic service that
comes into every cable subscriber's home. 
<dd>In his new book Slouching Toward Gomorrah: Modern Liberalism and American Decline, Robert Bork suggests that maybe it is time to re-instate censorship in America. "From the earliest colonies on this continent over 300 years ago, and for about 175 years of our existence as a nation, we endorsed and lived with censorship," Bork argues. That changed dramatically in 1973 when the Supreme Court in Miller vs. California established new standards to determine what may be banned. Courts since then have been reluctant to ban any sexual material as long as it involves "consenting adults." 
<dd>Barely 50 years ago, Bork reminds us, the Supreme Court unanimously wrote: "There are certain well-defined and narrowly limited classes of speech, the prevention and punishment of which have never been thought to raise any Constitutional problem. These include the lewd and obscene, the profane, the libelous, and the insulting or 'fighting' words." 
<dd>How far we've come since then. Now the First Amendment is regularly invoked to protect as "speech" forms of expression that include "snuff" films that depict the sexual torture and murder of women and children, photographs and videos of men and women having sex with animals, and other abominations too numerous to mention. 
<dd>It is unimaginable that our Founders would have sanctioned this interpretation of the First Amendment, which after all was intended originally to protect political speech deemed necessary for democracy to function, indeed thrive. Are we a freer society today by virtue of being exposed to all manner of filth and smut? Are our children more likely to grow up good, informed citizens ready to perform their democratic duties because they have listened to a steady stream of misogynist and hedonist rock and rap lyrics on the public airwaves? 
<dd>Unless the Supreme Court can see its way out of the morass it has created, maybe it is time to consider amending the First Amendment. Twenty-five years of radical First Amendment jurisprudence on pornography has turned much of the popular culture into a Styxian cesspool. And those of us who would like to avoid being drowned there are told we are anti-democratic. 
<dd>Why must I carefully avoid scanning television channels, or pretend I don't hear the suggestive words emanating from the radio when I take a taxi? Why must I look at sneering, crotch-clutching models in their underwear on the side of city buses? And how am I expected to protect my children if I choose? 
<dd>Surely liberty is not synonymous with licentiousness. And if judges cannot tell the difference, the people will have to show them the way, which is what real democracy is all about. 
<p>
<i>
<center>Linda Chavez, a syndicated columnist, is a member of<b> USA TODAY's</b> board of contributors.
<br>     
<p>
Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>.     
</i>
<br>
<br>
</center>
<hr>
<center><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></center>
</body>
</blockquote></blockquote>
