*Leap Year makes TFD, SFD, and COGD appear one day earlier
<UL>
<LI>1  Based on Tax Foundation figures
<LI>2  SFD measures the cost of total government outlays (taxes plus borrowing)
<LI>3  COGD incorporates total (federal, state, and local) government expenditures, federal regulatory costs, and state workers' compensation and tort law costs.  COGD data is based on information compiled by Americans for Tax Reform Foundation from data in the President's January 1996 budget baseline; Thomas D. Hopkins, "Costs of Regulation:  Filling the Gaps" (report prepared for the Regulatory Information Service Center, Washington, D.C.), August 1992; "Tort Cost Trends; An International Perspective" (report prepared by the Tillinghast Company), 1992; and independent data provided by the Dept. of Commerce, Bureau of Economic Analysis.</UL><P>






<FONT SIZE=+1><BOLD><a name="DEFINITION">Introduction to Cost of Government Day
</a></BOLD></FONT><P>
<BOLD>Definition</BOLD><BR>
Cost of Government Day is the day of the calendar year, counting form January 1, on which the average American worker has earned enough in gross income to pay off his or her federal, state, and local government-imposed financial obligations--total spending plus the cost of regulation.<P>

<BOLD>Methodology</BOLD><BR>
The cost of government is determined by adding the figures for government spending (all federal, state, and local outlays) and an estimate of the cost of government regulations.  A 1992 report prepared for the Regulatory Information Service Center by Rochester Institute of Technology Professor Thomas D. Hopkins provided the framework for determining the cost of regulations.  His figures were updated to include the cost of new regulations from information provided by economist Dr. Robert Genetski and estimates by Cost of Government Day director Alan Philp.  State workers' compensation and tort costs were included in the COGD figure as well, from information provided in a report produced by the Tillinghast Company.

<BOLD>What COGD Does/Does Not Include:</BOLD><BR>
<UL>
<LI>  All federal, state, and local outlays (taxes plus borrowing) are included in COGD.
<LI>  Most federal regulations are incorporated.  Exceptions include costs associated with minimum wage laws and anti-trust laws.
<LI> At the state level, only workers' compensation and tort costs  are incorporated.  Costs associated with state and local environmental protection, worker safety, and consumer protection are not included.  These costs, which are not included because the measurements cannot readily be quantified and broken out, can be substantial.
<LI> Indirect costs of regulation--resources diverted from other activities (e.g., decreased time with families, less leisure time) -- are not included.  Compliance costs, paperwork costs, and transfer costs are included.</UL></p>




<BOLD>Overview of the Cost of Government</BOLD><BR>
 
<P>
 <UL>
<LI> Cost of Government Day has moved forward for three straight years due to (1)sharp cuts in defense spending, (2)the defeat of Bill Clinton's government take-over of the health care system, and (3)a lessening in the number of major new regulations.  Had the Clinton health care plan passed, Cost of Government Day would have moved back approximately 30 days.  Americans would be working for the government an additional month.
<LI>  Because the 1996 House Republican budget became law, at least in 
part , Cost of Government Day came earlier than in 1995.  By 2000, Cost of Government Day will arrive at least 11 days earlier than scheduled under the Clinton plan.
<LI>  By 2002, the GOP budget will make Cost of Government Day arrive at least 17 days earlier than scheduled under the Clinton plan.  (This figure does not include additional savings from proposed Republican regulatory and legal reforms.)
<LI>  Republican legal reforms, if passed, will help rein in soaring civil justice costs, which now consume $300 billion per year, according to Citizens for a Sound Economy.<P></ul>





<A NAME="Facts About Regulation"><bold><font size=+1>Facts About Regulation</font><br>
Quantifying the Costs<bold><p>

<bold>Regulation Costs Jobs.</bold>  Economists Michael Hazilla and Raymond J. Kopp concluded that environmental regulations alone had by 1990 reduced the overall employment level by 1.18 percent.  According to economist Bill Laffer, that translates into 1.1 million to 1.4 million fewer jobs.  Laffer estimates the cost of all federal regulations numbers between 3.6 million and 9.6 million jobs.<br>
<ADDRESS>Sources:  Michael Hazilla and Raymond J. Kopp, "Social Cost of Environmental Quality Regulations:  A General Equilibrium Analysis," Journal of Political Economy, Vol. 98, No. 4 (1990), p.869; and William G. Laffer, "How Regulation is Destroying American Jobs," The Heritage Foundation:  16 February 1993, pp.6-7.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>The Costs of Affirmative Action:</bold><br>
A projection based on a Forbes magazine model finds that the direct compliance costs of affirmative action programs cost the nation $25 billion per year.  But indirect costs -- paperwork, loss of efficiency, etc. -- could exceed $100 billion per year, according to the study.  According to the Congressional Research Service, about 160 federal programs, statutes, regulations, and executive orders grant some measure of "preference" to women or minorities in the areas of hiring, federal contracts, educational opportunities and grants.<br>
<ADDRESS>Sources:  Peter Brimelow and Leslie Spencer, "When Quotas Replace Merit, Everybody Suffers," Forbes, February 15, 1993; and John F. Harris and Kevin Merida, "Political Consensus on Affirmative Action Evaporating," The Washington Post, April 5, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>
<bold>Losses to Farmers:</bold></br>
The American Farm Bureau  Federation estimates that U.S. agricultural interests spend between $18 billion and $20 billion per year complying with federal regulations.  To put things in perspective, that figure is roughly 35 percent of total net farm income in the United States.  If this estimate is in the ballpark, farmers spend $2 complying with government-mandated regulations for every $1 they receive in price supports.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Thad Cochran, "Regulatory Relief for Farmers," The Washington Times, April 4, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>The Cost of Cleanliness:</bold><br>
According to the U.S. Commerce Department, pollution abatement and control expenditures consumed more than 18 percent of gross private domestic nonresidential investment in 1992, or $102 billion.  Over the past 20 years, U.S. businesses have been forced to divert almost 15 percent of their total fixed investment to nonproductive equipment.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Bruce Bartlett, "The High Cost of Turning Green," The Wall Street Journal, September 14, 1994.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>Automobile Prices:</bold><br>
The cost of emissions-control equipment added to a new car through the 1994 model year averages $2010, according to data supplied by the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics and corrected to 1993 dollars.  Californians face a major dilemma in the coming years.  Regulators there have issued quotas of zero-emissions cars that they must build and sell, starting with 2 percent of the vehicles sold in California in 1998, then rising to five percent in 2001, and to 10 percent in 2003 and beyond.  This regulation promises almost no discernible benefits.  Every new car sold in the state today is 97% clean.  Most smog is produced by the dirtiest 10% of cars.  The 100 percent clean cars will replace the 97 percent clean cars, not the worst polluters.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Patrick Bedard, "Still Smoggy After All These Years," Car and Driver, April 1995</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>The Price Tag:</bold><br>
Government regulators regularly under-estimate the true cost of their proposed regulations.  The <ADDRESS>Federal Register</ADDRESS>  estimated that obtaining a stormwater discharge permit under the Clean Water Act would cost $76,681.  Gregory S. Lashutka, mayor of Columbus, Ohio, reports that his city's actual cost was $1.5 million.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Gregory S. Lashutka, "A Mayor's Plea:  Mandate No More," The Wall Street Journal, December 1, 1994.</ADDRESS><p>



<font size=+1><bold><a name="Recent Developements">Recent Develompments</a><br></font>
Smoking Regulations:</bold><br>
In what is estimated will cost $8.1 billion in the first year alone, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has marching order to go out and require restaurants, retailers, office buildings owners, and others to inspect and maintain their indoor ventilation systems and ban cigarette smoking unless it takes place in separately ventillated rooms.  Government regulators have launched a crusade to stamp out smoking, based on "studies" showing secondhand smoke to be a health menace.  But the 1.19 risk ration for intensive, 40 year, day-in-day-out, pack-a-day exposure to secondhand smoke is by virtually all measures insignificant.<br><ADDRESS>Source:  Susan Eckerly, "Seeking a Regulatory Respite," The Washington Times, February 12, 1995; and Jerry Taylor, "Cancer Risks for Thee, but Not for Me," The Wall Street Journal, January 3, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>Water Quality Standards:</bold><br>
In March, the EPA's Great Lakes Initiative imposed uniform standards for water quality on eight different states (Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Minnesota, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin).  A study conducted for the Council of Great Lakes Governors says this will cost more than $2 billion per year and destroy up to 33,000 jobs.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Susan Eckerly, "Seeking a Regulatory Respite," The Washington Times, February 12, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>Air Pollution Standards:</bold><br>
Californians face $4 to $6 billion more to federal air quality regulatory costs each year.  Environmental Protection Agency regulators are marching into Los Angeles, Sacramento, and Ventura to enforce compliance with the 1977 Clean Air Act.  The state of California estimates that by 2010, "losses will total at least $8.4 billion in direct costs, $17.2 billion in output, and 165,000 jobs."<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Susan Eckerly, "Seeking a Regulatory Respite," The Washington Times, February 12, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>Ethanol:</bold><br>
Bill Clinton frequently chooses to use regulatory dictates to reward favorite industries and constituencies.  Bowing to the powerful corn lobby, Clinton last year adopted the so-called ethanol rule, guaranteeing ethanol a 30 percent share of the oxygenate market for the reformulated gasoline program.  Ethanol is typically more expensive than its alternative, an ether known as MTBE.  Clinton's ethanol mandate was on track to cost consumers as much as $350 million per year at the gasoline pump (on top of his gas tax) and would have deprived the National Highway Trust Fund of millions of dollars of revenues because ethanol is partially tax exempt.  In April, 1995, the D.C. Circuit Court of Appeals delivered Clinton at least a temporary setback, ruling Clinton exceeded his authority with the ethanol mandate.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Jonathan Adler, "Alternative Fuel Follies with Ethanol Vapors," The Washington Times, May 3, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>The ADA's Legal Quagmire:</bold><br>
By December, 1994, nearly 40,000 complaints were filed under the Americans with Disabilities Act.  But mounting evidence suggests massive abuse.  Eighty-five percent of complaints came from people who had jobs, one-fifth of complaints came from people with back trouble, and nearly 12 percent from those with emotional or psychiatric impairments.  These figures suggest a large amount of administrative and legal activity for an apparently modest return, considering that Congress intended to design an incentive-based approach to broadening opportunities for the disabled.<br><ADDRESS>Source:  Claudia Winkler, "Reality Check on ADA's Results," The Washington Times, April 20, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>
<bold>FDA Tyranny:</bold><br>The Food and Drug Administration will soon require food manufacturers to notify the FDA before marketing foods manufactured with new biotech techniques -- high precision recombinant DNA, or gene splicing techniques.  This move reflects a two-year trend at the FDA toward stricter scrutiny of biotech products, relying more on "risk considerations" than real science.<br><ADDRESS>Source:  Henry Miller, "Dr. Kessler's Regulatory Obsessions," The Washington Times, December 15, 1994.</ADDRESS><p>

<bold>Banks Lose:</bold><br>
The American Bankers Association estimates that Bill Clinton's new "community reinvestment" requirements for banks will add more than $150 million in administrative costs to the industry.<br><ADDRESS>Source:  John Merline, "How Clinton Will Regulate U.S.," Investor's Business Daily, April 19, 1994.</ADDRESS></p>






<font=+1><a name="Regulatory Horror Stories">Regulatory Horror Stories</font><P>

In Sacramento, California, residents are reeling over a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service ruling last fall which added three varieties of the fairy shrimp to th endangered species list.  The agency relied upon a one-paragraph petition submitted by a Davis, Calif., botanist in 1990, even though millions of the hardy shrimp can be found in California, Europe, Asia, Australia and Africa.  The decision has shut down a pony ranch that housed a Sacramento program for needy and disabled children and could cost the Sacramento-area housing industry $550 million.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Editorial, The Wall Street Journal, October 21, 1994.</ADDRESS><p>

Pushing forward with the next stage of the 1990 Clean Air Act, the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has created a new paperwork nightmare for companies in high smog urban areas called the Employee Commute Option (ECO).  Employers in these regions are forced to find ways to cajole a designated percentage of their workers into carpools -- or face devastating financial penalties that can reach as high as $25,000 per violation.  Eric Peters, an automotive writer for <ADDRESS>The Washington Times</ADDRESS> observes that "the real genius of the ECO mandate is that it turns employers -- not the government or the EPA -- into the bullyboy."
<ADDRESS><br>Source:  Eric Peters, "Coercive Carpooling in View Via EPA Fiat," The Washington Times, September 17, 1994.</ADDRESS><p>

The EPA also announced new emissions standards for marine engines, one of the last unregulated emissions sources.  Since marine engines are responsible for only about three percent of total emissions, the new standards are unlikely to have any noticeable effect on air quality.  But consumers will notice.  The high-performance, fuel-injected marine engines necessary to comply with the mandate can cost $1,200 (15%) more than conventional engines, a nationwide cost of as much as $300 million per year.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Jonathan Adler, "Motorboat Madness at the EPA," The Washington Times, November 18, 1994.</ADDRESS><p>

Food and Drug Administration rules implemented by FDA head David Kessler are costing lives.  In 1991, Dr. Kessler prohibited pharmaceutical companies from informing doctors of new uses for approved drugs.  In one instance, the FDA stopped a pharmaceutical company from distributing free copies of "The Chemotherapy Source Book"--even though the company had already received FDA approval to give away thousands of copies.  The FDA claims that when a drug company gives doctors free textbooks that mention an off-label use of its products, the drugs become subject to seizure.<br><ADDRESS>Source:  James Bovard, "First Step to an FDA Cure:  Dump Kessler,"  The Wall Street Journal, December 8, 1994.</ADDRESS><p>

Bob Floyd of Muncie, Ind., had a "wetland" mysteriously appear on his property when a local business accidentally cut a drainage pipe.  Federal regulators swooped in to protect this "wetland" and forced the 80-year-old farmer to stop farming.  The so-called wetland has since dried up, but Mr. Floyd may have to sell the land his family has farmed for a half century.
<ADDRESS><br>Source:  Thad Cochrane, "Regulatory Reliedf for Farmers," The Washington Times, April 4, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>
Bob Lindberg, president of Young Co. in Seattle, thought his small metal firm had a decent diversity record -- with a work force that included about 35 percent women and minorities -- until the Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs (OFCCP) came knocking on his door.  The agency accused the firm, which is a subcontractor for a company that supplies anchors to the Navy, of a number of charges including failing to hire qualified Asian applicants.  Young opened his books to the auditors, spent thousands of dollars on a consultant, and finally settled in part by paying $47,000 in back wages to some minority workers.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  John F. Harris and Kevin Merida, "Political Consensus on Affirmative Action Evaporating," The Washington Post, April 5, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>
John Thorpe's plans to build on his own property were thwarted by the Fish and Wildlife Service, which demanded to know what steps he had taken to preserve the salt marsh harvest mouse.  Though Mr. Thorpe only wanted to develop mostly on the dry, upland portion of his propery, an agency of the U.S. government theorized that when golboal warming melts the polar ice-caps, the Pacific will rise and inundate the habitat of the salt marsh harvest mouse on his lowlands, forcing it to seek refuge on Thorpe's highlands.  For this science fiction story, Thorpe was denied permission to develope his land.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Cal Thomas, "Tales of Trepidation from the Regulation Crypt," The Washington Times, May 10, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>
Creighton Hale, CEO of Little League Baseball, described on the pages of the Wall Street Journal a case in which a volunteer coach was sued for punitive damages and pain and suffering after one of his youthful outfielders was beaned by a pop fly.<br><ADDRESS>Source:  Editorial, The Wall Street Journal, March 7, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>

Richard Enthoven's family-owned Kwik Wash Laundries Inc. in Dallas says it is facing damage claims totaling more than $2 million in two suits.  In a high-crime neighborhood in San Antonio three years ago, a man was murdered near the entrance of one apartment building launderette, where he was washing a friend's clothes at about 2 a.m.  E.B. Barretto, the attorney representing the victim's father, alleges that Kwik Wash failed to provide adequate security at its launderette.  He further claims a security light was out and Kwik Wash violated the apartment building's safety guidelines, which called for closing the launderette at 10 p.m.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Michael Salz and Jeffrey A. Tannenbaum,"Scared of Lawsuits, Small Businesses Applaud Reform," The Wall Street Journal, March 13, 1995.</address><p>

In an example of the lawsuit frenzy borne of the 1990 Americans with Disabilities Act, in July, 1992, GTE Data Services in Tampa discovered that one of its computer programmers had been stealing money from other employees and had brought a loaded derringer to work.  When he was fired for having the gun, he sued for reinstatement under the ADA.  He said he was the victim of a mental illness aggravated by improper medication , and thus disabled under the language of the act.  The first court ruling - later overturned -- went in the programmer's favor:  "When poor judgment is a sympton of a mental or psychological disorder, it is defined as an impairment that would qualify as a disability under the ADA," the court said.
<ADDRESS><br>Source:  Jay Matthews,"Disabilities Act Failing to Achieve Workplace Goals," The Washington Post, April 16, 1995.</ADDRESS><p>

David and Florence Isbell -- well known in activist legal circles in Washington -- teamed up with the Washington Lawyers' Committee to force Washington area theaters to install special assistive listening devices.  Cineplex theaters, the unfortunate target of the Isbell's crusade, had been installing the equipment in theaters around the nation when the Isbell's filed suit.  In response, Cineplex accelerated the installation plan for the Washington area and had all theaters equipped by August 31.  Thinking the problem had been solved, Cineplex asked the U.S. District court to dismiss the suit.  The lead attorney for the Washington Lawyers' Committee refused to back down.  Cineplex ageed to pay $60,000 in attorneys' fees and accept the supervision of a court appointed monitor.  Howard Lichtman, executive vice president of the Cineplex chain, says the rate of requests for the devices "is infinitesimal."
<ADDRESS><br>Source:  Jay Mathews, " The Washington Case that Took the Rights Act to the Movies,"  The Washington Post, April 16, 1995.</address><p>

When a club at the East Brunswick Condominium Association in New Jersey set aside some swimming pool hours exclusively for adults, the Civil Rights Division of the Justice Department swept in, alleging a violation of the Fair Housing Act for discrimination against children.  For this transgression, the association was obligated to pay $3,000 in compensatory damages, enroll its employees in nondiscrimination training, and report its policies to the Justice Department for the next four years.<br>
<ADDRESS>Source:  Clint Bolick, "Extortion Not Enforcement, by the Civil Rights Division," The Wall Street Journal, April 5, 1995.</ADDRESS><p><p>







<font size=+1><bold><a name="An Agenda for Reform in 1996">An Agenda for Reform in 1996</a></font></bold><p>

The Republican Congress should set specific goals for the movement of Cost of Government Day.  Specifically, legislators should target a Cost of Government Day 1996 on or before July 4th, so that Americans can truly enjoy their liberation from the government on Independence Day.  Likewise, Congress should aim for a Cost of Government Day 2005 on or before April 15th so Americans can truly enjoy the fruits of the labor by the time they file their taxes.<p>

Heighten public attention about "bureaucratic tyranny" by establishing a monthly "Corrections Day" and holding public "show trials" of wasteful government programs and abusive regulations.  "Corrections Day," as dubbed by Speaker Gingrich, would help stem "self-evidently stupid," "profoundly dumb," "stupidly legal" and "silly" regulations flowing from federal agencies.
<address><br>Source:  Kenneth Cooper, "Speaker is planning a Bash for Bureaucratic Boondoggles, "The Washington Post, May 3, 1995.</address><p>

Bar unelected federal bureaucrats from making laws.  Ultimately, no law should go into effect without the consent of a majority of the House, a majority of the Senate, and the signature of the President.  Lawmakers should take direct responsibility for laws by enacting them themselves.  Agency bureaucrats can make recommendations, conduct risk assessment, and propose legal language, but should not be allowed to make laws themselves.<br>
<address>Source:  David Schoenbrod, "On Environmental Law, Congress Keeps Passing the Buck, "The Wall Street Journal, March 29, 1995.</address><p>
Reduce the number of government regulators.  From 1985 to 1992, staffing of federal regulatory agencies increased by over 20 percent.  By 1992, the federal government employed almost 125,000 regulatory employees, and that total has increased under Bill Clinton.  One way Congress can reduce "bureaucratic tyranny," as Speaker Gingrich has described it, is by reducing the number of government regulators.  Too often, regulators seek to justify their own existence by implementing time consuming and overly bureaucratic mandates on state and local governments and private businesses. <p> Congress should send regulators a message:  Overzealous regulatory behavior will be punished, not rewarded.  State and local governments must follow suit.  During the 1980's, state-level bureaucracies increased by almost 20 percent.  Whereas the federal government employes about two million civilian employees, state and local governments employ more than six times that amount.<br>
<address>Source:  Jonathan Adler, "On a High Regulatory Roll,"  The Washington Times, April 4, 1994.</address><p> 

Demand proper risk assessment of all proposed regulations.  Government regulators are notorious for devoting huge resources to relatively insignificant risks -- like asbestos exposure in schools -- at tremendous cost to companies and consumers.  For example, look at EPA's risk assessment for a Superfund site.  You will learn about hypothetical children who eat dirt 250 days a year from the bottom of contaminated brooks and ponds.  Likewise, the Safe Drinking Water Act mandates that local governments get rid of virtually all chloroform in their water, even though the best available science suggests that chloroform does not pose a danger in the biological mechanisms associated with drinking tap water.  Risk assessment should quantify the cost of all proposed regulations and rank risks in order of priority.  Target risks should be compared to several ordinary risks that people confront in their daily lives.  In addition, regulators should be required to consider competing risks -- dangers induced by regulators.  For example, Corporate Average Fuel Economy standards requiring "fuel efficient" automobiles are resulting in smaller, less safe cars and more deaths and injuries on the road.<br>
<address>Source:  John D. Graham, "Regulation:  A Risky Business," The Wall Street Journal, May 18, 1994.</address><p>

Enact a federal regulatory budget.  Such a budget would establish a maximum total regulatory burden that government could impose on the economy.  Any new regulations that would exceed the budget based on risk assessment reports would require the repeal or modification of some other regulations to ensure regulatory burden neutrality.<br>
<address>Source:  William G. Laffer, "How Regulations are Destroying American Jobs,"  The Heritage Foundation Backgrounder, February 16, 1993.</address><p>


Overhaul the Clean Air Act and allow states to use remote-sensing detectors to identify high-emission vehicles.  Just 10 percent of the cars on the road produce half of all hydrocarbons.  But current law subjects the 90 percent of clean auto owners to cumbersome, expensive, time-consuming, bureaucracy-intensive mandates such as inspections, reformulated gasolines, car-pooling requirements, alternative fuels, and even soon-to-be mandated production of inefficient electric cars in California.  Remote-sensing technology can identify dirt cars, reducing the role of government and freeing most auto-owners from bureaucratic harassment.<br>
<address>Source:  Patrick Bedard, "Still Smoggy After All These Years," Car and Driver, April, 1995.</address><p>

Reform the 1974 Clean Water Act to specifically and reasonably define what constitutes a wetland.  Under current rules, federal regulators have construed the Clean Water Act to classify huge tracts of land as wetlands for protection from development, even though the 1974 statute says nothing about welands protection.  Bipartisan legislation sponsored by Rep. Bud Shuster calling on the Army Corps of Engineers and the Department of Agriculture to classify all existing welands based on function and environmental importance into categoies A (high priority), B (modest priority) and C (low priority)  would put an end to egregious bureaucratic regulatory "takings" from private land-owners.<br>
<address>Sources:  Gary Lee and Curt Suplee, "Debate to Begin on Clean Water Act Revision, " The Washington Post, May 10, 1995; and Joyce Price, "Wetlands Overhaul Draws Wide Support," The Washington Times, May 11, 1995.</address><p>

Provide for proper enforcement of the Fifth Amendment's "takings" clause.  Landowners should be compensated for all substantial reductions in their property values which result from enforcement of federal, state, or local regulatory statutes.<br>
<address>Source:  Marc LaFountain, "Senate Bill Seeks Property Protection,"  The Washington Times, March 24, 1995.</address><p>

Repeal the Delaney Clause, a provision of the 1958 Food Drug and Cosmetic Act that allows only additives deemed to have zero risk of causing cancer to be used on processed foods.  Passed at a time when cancer risks were far more difficult to determine, the statute is grossly outdated at best and an example of hyper-regulatory overkill at worst.<br>
source:  Gary Lee and Cindy Skrzycki, "Panel Pushes Risk Assessment Bill,"  The Washington Post, April 28, 1995.</address><p>
Enact Long-awaited Banking Reform.  Existing banking laws -- largely incorporated in the 1930's-era Glass-Seagall Act -- are woefully outdated, sharply restricting or prohibiting the ability of banks to expand across state lines, sell insurance, or provide investment underwriting.  As a result, American banks are at a tremendous disadvantage in the world market.  Congress should repeal antiquated laws such as the Glass-Seagall Act and promote competition in the American banking industry.  A recent McKinsey & Co. study found that the annual costs of interstate banking under today's cumbersome regulatory structure can range from .5 percent to almost one percent of a company's noninterest expenses -- a total in the billions of dollars.  And these savings are dwarfed by those that will come from the nationwide consolidations of operations.
<br><address>Source:  Greg Wilson, "Interstate Banking -- Now,"The Wall Street Journal, March 16, 1994.</address><p>

Repeal market regulations on telecommunications providers.  The long distance and local telephone markets, as well as the cable television market, should be opened up to competition.  Current law, based on the 1934 Communications Act based on 19th century railroad regulation, imposes restrictions which ensure virtual monopolies in existing phone and cable markets.  These antiquated regulations should come to an end, and the cable-telco ban, which prevents telephone and cable firms from competing against each other, should be repealed.  Competition between long distance and local phone companies and cable television providers will reduce prices and ensure better service for consumers.  The 1992 Cable Act should be repealed.
<br><address>Sources:  Adam D. Thierer, "A Guide to Telecommunications Deregulation Legislation," Heritage Foundation Issue Bulletin No. 191, June 3, 1994; and Caroly Lochhead, "Congress in Turmoil Over Telecom Deregulations," San Francisco Chronicle, February 7, 1995.</address><p>

Enact Civil Justice Refomr.  The more than 70,000 product liability lawsuits filed in the United States each year cost Americans $300 billion per year, according to Citizens for a Sound Economy.  It's no wonder 47 percent of U.S. firms in a recent survey said they had withdrawn products from the market over fear of lawsuits.  Congress must pass comprehensive legal reform, including partial institution of a "loser-pays" rule to encourage settlements, a cap on "pain-and-suffering" awards in all civil suits, higher standards of proof for punitive damages in all civil suits, and limits on the liability of manufacturers.<br>
<Address>Source:  Monday RNC Briefing, "Focus:  Lawsuit Abuse Reforms," March 13, 1995.</address>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT15-B20-172</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA036-000708-B017-268</DOCOLDNO>
