<HEAD>

<TITLE> An E-Burst to Dow's Place  -- PFF</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<br><br>
<h2>An E-Burst to Dow's Place </h2>
</B>
<P>
<B>By <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Vlahos"> Michael Vlahos</a></B><BR>

<P>
<I><p>20 March, 2006.</I>
<p>

My cryptagent made the discovery.  It sure looked like a break-in:  the wreckage of 512bit crypto code, address shreds from bolted folders, a corrupted cache. I sure hope the CC boys found what they were looking for.
<P>
How did it happen that the Government now routinely reads what we write and say in the ether?  That sure wasn't the intention, back when the Telecommunications Act of 1996 passed.  The idea then was that very restricted language would be inserted that would protect our children.  I even remember the scene at a certain Wednesday meeting:  The "Family" alliance was making a big stink about "smut on the internet," and when we barely whispered, "censorship," they got even angrier.<I>  "See this language," they </i>and their conference committee champions said,<i> "this does nothing to inhibit free speech.  We're just taking the Pacifica definition of obscenity that everyone agrees with.  And look!  We even put in a paragraph that tells the FCC it has no power to enforce any of this!"</i>
<P>
How could you argue with that, especially when that particular staffer's hands were shaking with righteousness?  We all had similar run-ins.  We didn't want to alienate our friends on the side of the angels, so we let it pass.
<P>
We forgot the great truth about government in the last century:  legislation to do good for all ends up as government's authority to control us.  The Income Tax, Prohibition, the Draft, Citizens with Disabilities, the Clean Air Act, the Tobacco Control Act of '02;  all were designed to help people, boost the general welfare, promote civic virtue.  
<P>
But they were designed to achieve all these good things by fiat from above.  Today, so many of us think these laws pure tyranny, but the laws themselves did not enslave us.  We need to look elsewhere for that, to the ethos of rule.
<P>
The late-lamented twentieth century saw the maturation and old age of an industrial world.  It was a world of pyramids run from the top down, where those who made it to the top were called "the best and the brightest."  Law and Ivy credentials gave them the authority to call themselves<i> managers </i> (the equestrian rank of those days).  But they were not content to use this authority merely to rule.  They wanted to<i> help</I> people;  and they knew,
<i>O best and brightest,</I> that they had the smarts and the heart to do it.
<P>
They were<i> Progressives.</I>  The whole of the last century was informed by the urgent need for smart people to uplift everyone else.  And only they knew how.  And only they could do it.
<P>
This ethos of rule naturally inclined toward laws that would let the best and brightest do their good work right away.  But to do this, progressives needed not just authority;  they needed control.  Their reasoning:  <i>People will never do right on their own:  just look at the chaos and abuse of an open system.  People have to be told what to do.  The more they do what we say, the better things will be.</I>       
<P>
No, this was not Stalin's kind of control.  Not exactly.
<P>
Even now it is hard for us to believe that people who called themselves <i>Liberal and Progressive </I>for so long longed only to bring us a kinder and gentler Gulag.  But look at what they have done:
<P>
It's true, the language in the Telecom Act of '96 was careful.  FCC enforcement of the censorship provision <i>(what else can I call it!)</I> was forbidden.  The problem was, it was there in the first place.  We failed because we were worrying about the wrong problem.
<P>
We worried about "porn on the internet;"  or we were vulnerable, in some celestial way, to entreaties for the welfare of our children.  So we let a bill pass that gave progressive government still more authority over our lives.  The "Family" alliance was thinking,<i> Save our Children!,</I> but someone else was thinking,<i> I can do the protecting!</I>    
<P>
We then gave the Fed the implicit charge to go out and protect us some more.  Not the FCC.  Oh no.  The law said they could not enforce.  But there were scads of Federal agencies aching to enforce.  And enforce they did.  If the FCC was barred from enforcement, it was not denied the right of assistance.  And assist they did.
<P>
And those NSA geeks (don't tell me it was just CC boys) busting into my cache?  I knew it would happen eventually.  My encryption engine exceeded the Federal legal rating  and it was in use.  Like the old radar detectors, we all have them;  they're only illegal if you use them.  And since they're too hard to crack in volume, we get by.  We need 512 bits, for plain old privacy.
<P>
So that was how the Telecom language intended to protect us become our scourge:  All porn has to be encrypted, but encryption that works is illegal to use!  Since the porn guys have been giving away 512b engines and keys for free, the Feds say this means most kids can get it<i> (if you ignore the '000s of parental control products!). </I> So our Protectors have their probable cause <i>and</I> their slogan:<i>  For the children!</I>
<P>
I just hope it took them a nice long time to break in.  I left them a nice <i>.gif </I>of Manet's <i>Olympia.</I>  Good thing I've got the latest 1024b kernel on my hand-held.  At least they haven't started search and seizure
<P>
Yet. 
<P>
<P>
</blockquote><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>
</body>
</html>

