<h2>
Legislative Update</h2>
<b>Hot Issues:</b><p>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/dale.html">Travelgate</a> <i>(9/11)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/pbab.html">Partial Birth Abortions</a> <i>(9/19)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/health.html">Health Care</a> <i>(4/25)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/minwage.html">Minimum Wage</a> <i>(4/20)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/immigration.html">Immigration</a> <i>(3/21)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/allwhite.html">Whitewater</a> <i>(3/25)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/barr.html">Public Safety</a> <i>(3/25)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/nga.html">Welfare Reform</a> <i>(3/25)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/senpliab.html">Product Liability Reform</a> <i>(3/25)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/sens942.html">Small Business Deregulation</a> <i>(3/25)</i>
<br><a href="/conservative/hotissues/taiwan.html">Taiwan</a> <i>(3/25)</i>

</center>
<hr>
<p>
<I><FONT SIZE ="+2">W</FONT>elcome</I> to the American Conservative Union's "Legislative Update" page.  On this page you will
find regular updates on the key legislation we are tracking, as the legislation moves from
introduction to subcommittee and committee hearings, subcommittee and committee markups,
and floor action in both the House and Senate.  On any given day, this is where you can get the
latest information available on the key issues conservatives care about.
<P>
As the nation's oldest conservative grass-roots lobbying organization, founded more than three
decades ago, the ACU sees its proper role as being the grass-roots lobby for the entire
Conservative Movement.  As such, we are not a single-issue organization.  Our officers, staff, and
-- most importantly -- our members are motivated toward public policy activism by the shared
beliefs explained in the ACU Statement of Principles.
<P>
Because the ACU is a multi-issue, umbrella organization, we monitor and lobby on a wide range
of issues before the Congress.  For ease in tracking those various pieces of legislation, we have
broken them down into four general categories:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Economic and Budget issues (examples:  the Balanced Budget Amendment; the Tax
     Limitation Amendment; the Budget Resolution; tax legislation; health care reform
     legislation; legislation to raise the debt ceiling; the Mexico bailout; etc.)
<LI>Social and Cultural issues (examples:  the Crime Bill; welfare reform; a school prayer
     amendment; abortion legislation; homosexual rights legislation; educational choice; etc.)
<li>Foreign Policy and Defense issues (examples:  ballistic missile defenses; the United
Nations; Bosnia; Haiti; the foreign aid bill; the War Powers Act; etc.)
<LI>Institutional Reform issues (examples:  term limits; campaign finance reform; budget
     process reform; repeal of the 16th Amendment, which instituted the income tax; lobbying
     reform; etc.)

</UL>
<p>
